{"sections":[],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Learn the basics of working with Swift source code with the SwiftSyntax library."}],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftsyntax\/working-with-swiftsyntax"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"minor":3,"major":0},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax"]]},"kind":"article","seeAlsoSections":[{"anchor":"Articles","generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/Macro-Versioning","doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/RawSyntaxValidation","doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/Glossary"],"title":"Articles"}],"metadata":{"title":"Working with SwiftSyntax","role":"article","modules":[{"name":"SwiftSyntax"}],"roleHeading":"Article"},"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/Working-with-SwiftSyntax","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Overview","anchor":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The SwiftSyntax library provides data structures and algorithms for inspecting,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"processing, and manipulating Swift source code with a high-level, safe, and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"efficient API. The SwiftSyntax library is the foundation upon which tools like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the Swift parser, swift-format, and Swift macros are built."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Syntax Trees","anchor":"Syntax-Trees"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"SwiftSyntax is a library for representing Swift source code with a data structure"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"called a "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"syntax tree"}]},{"type":"text","text":". The structure of a syntax tree reflects not just the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"relative order and position of text and whitespace in a file"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"- its “lexical structure” - but also the relationship between nested syntactic"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"elements and their neighbors - its “syntactic structure”."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The syntax tree was designed with three tenets in mind:"}]},{"level":3,"anchor":"Immutability","text":"Immutability","type":"heading"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The syntax tree is a fully immutable "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Persistent_data_structure","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Once created, the syntax tree never changes, and may only be modified by"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"creating a new syntax tree. The SwiftSyntax library provides a number of APIs"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"for modifying an existing syntax tree efficiently and safely. It does so by"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"copying only the minimal amount of structure that has changed into the new"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"tree. Any unchanged structure from the original tree becomes part of a shared"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"core that is transparently wrapped by the new syntax tree. In this way, the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"SwiftSyntax library reuses and shares as much data as possible during syntactic"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"transformations. This reduces the overall memory footprint and the overhead"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"normally associated with copying large and complex data structures like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"syntax trees."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Immutability also comes with the benefits of fearless concurrency. It is always","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"safe to manipulate a syntax tree across threads. Two threads mutating the same","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"tree will receive two independent copies of their respective modified syntax","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"trees that will never interfere with each other. Moreover, modifications to","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the syntax tree do not involve locks or mutexes.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Source-Fidelity","text":"Source Fidelity"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The SwiftSyntax library is designed to represent not just text, but"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"whitespace, comments, compiler directives, and otherwise invisible data like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the "},{"identifier":"https:\/\/unicode.org\/faq\/utf_bom.html","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":". Collectively, these non-syntax entities are"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"referred to as “trivia”. The syntax tree holds on to every byte of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"information in the source text, and can render the original document"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with full accuracy and precision. This property is referred to as"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"“source fidelity”, because the syntax tree is always a faithful recreation of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the source code it was given as input."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Resilience","text":"Resilience"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To achieve source fidelity, both well-formed and ill-formed source code must"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"be equally representable in the syntax tree. The syntax tree can represent two"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"broad classes of errors: missing syntax and unexpected syntax. Missing syntax"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"provides a spot for a syntax element that was expected by a parser or lexical"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"analyzer but was not present in source."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["func (uhoh: Void) {}","     ^ Missing identifier"]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Missing syntactic elements are represented in the tree as tokens with a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SourcePresence\/missing","type":"reference"},{"text":" source presence. These missing tokens are just as","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"much a part of the syntax tree as ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SourcePresence\/present","type":"reference"},{"text":" nodes, and","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"can be inspected and manipulated as normal syntax. One important use-case is","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"a “healing linter” which can examine missing nodes and fill in keywords,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"identifiers, and placeholders as appropriate in addition to warning about","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"syntactic nits.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Unexpected syntax is any superfluous text encountered by a parser or lexical"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"analyzer."}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["func four score and seven years ago(uhoh: Void) {}","          ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ Unexpected text"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Unexpected nodes allow parsers to gracefully recover during parsing by scanning","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"forward in the input stream until they reach a known recovery point. The","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"Swift parser included with the swift-syntax package uses this implementation","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"strategy to great effect. This makes the parser resilient to a broad","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"class of input errors that users of editors and IDEs would make during the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"course of an editing session.","type":"text"}]},{"anchor":"Syntax-Nodes","type":"heading","text":"Syntax Nodes","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"A syntax tree is made up of elements called syntax nodes. To help categorize","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and organize syntax nodes, SwiftSyntax defines a hierarchy of protocols for","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"syntax nodes. At the top of this hierarchy is the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxProtocol","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" protocol."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"To represent related categories of syntax, "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxProtocol","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" is further"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"refined:"}]},{"items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/DeclSyntaxProtocol"},{"type":"text","text":" for declarations like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"struct"},{"type":"text","text":"s, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"class"},{"type":"text","text":"es, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"enum"},{"text":"s and ","type":"text"},{"code":"protocol","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"s.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/StmtSyntaxProtocol","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" for statements like ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"if"},{"text":", ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"switch"},{"text":", and ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"do"},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ExprSyntaxProtocol"},{"text":" for expressions like function calls, literals, and closures","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/TypeSyntaxProtocol","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" for types like ","type":"text"},{"code":"Array<String>","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", ","type":"text"},{"code":"[String: String]","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", and ","type":"text"},{"code":"some Protocol","type":"codeVoice"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/PatternSyntaxProtocol","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" for patterns like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"case (_, let x)"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Syntax nodes form the “branches” of the syntax tree, as they are generally"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"high-level collections of one or more syntax nodes. Taken together, these"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"branches form the syntactic structure of the source code. This structure is","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"used by compilers and static analyzers to process source code at a high level.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A special kind of syntax node is a "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxCollection","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":", which represents syntax"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with a variable number of children. For example, a code block value can contain"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"zero or more statements in between a pair of braces. To represent these"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"children, a "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/CodeBlockSyntax"},{"type":"text","text":" value has a "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/CodeBlockSyntax\/statements","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":""},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"accessor that returns a "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/CodeBlockItemListSyntax"},{"type":"text","text":" value. The elements of this"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"syntax collection are "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/CodeBlockItemSyntax","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"text":" values.","type":"text"}]},{"anchor":"Syntax-Tokens","text":"Syntax Tokens","type":"heading","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"At the leaves of the syntax tree are "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/TokenSyntax","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" values. A token syntax"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"value represents an atomic unit of syntax and any associated trivia, like an"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"identifier and the whitespace around it. Taken together, the tokens of a syntax","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"tree represent the lexical structure of the source code. This structure is used"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"by linters and formatters to analyze the textual content of source code."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Syntax Trivia","anchor":"Syntax-Trivia"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Trivia includes whitespace, comments, compiler directives, and erroneous source","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"code. Trivia contributes most meaningfully to the lexical structure of a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"document, but often has little bearing on its syntactic structure. For this","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"reason, tools like compilers often discard trivia during source code processing.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"However, maintaining trivia is important for tools like editors, IDEs,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"formatters, and refactoring engines. SwiftSyntax represents trivia explicitly","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"with the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/Trivia","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" type. Trivia associated with token syntax can be inspected","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"with  the ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/TokenSyntax\/leadingTrivia","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/TokenSyntax\/trailingTrivia","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" accessors."}]},{"level":2,"type":"heading","anchor":"Navigating-the-Syntax-Tree","text":"Navigating the Syntax Tree"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The SwiftSyntax library provides a number of ways of traversing the syntactic"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"structure of a syntax tree. Every syntax node includes a reference to its"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"parent node via the "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxProtocol\/parent","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" accessor, and a reference to its","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"child nodes via the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxProtocol\/children(viewMode:)","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" method. The children","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of a syntax tree always appear in order and the associated ","type":"text"},{"code":"viewMode","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" allows","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the client to express their intent to process missing and unexpected syntax."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Syntax nodes also contain strongly-typed APIs to access those same child nodes"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"individually. For example, "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ClassDeclSyntax"},{"type":"text","text":" provides an"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ClassDeclSyntax\/identifier"},{"type":"text","text":" to get the name of the class, as well as"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ClassDeclSyntax\/members"},{"type":"text","text":" to get the syntax node representing the braced block"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with its members."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Most syntax analyzers want to work with more than one kind of syntax at a time,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and traverse this syntax in a regular order starting from the root and working"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"towards the leaves. SwiftSyntax provides a standard suite of classes and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"protocols for working with syntax traversals with a visitor-style API."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxVisitor"},{"type":"text","text":" can be used to walk source code from the root to its leaves."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"To inspect a particular kind of syntax node, a client needs to override the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"corresponding "},{"code":"visit","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" method accepting that kind of syntax. The visit methods"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"are invoked as part of an in-order traversal of the syntax tree. To provide a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"post-order traversal, the corresponding "},{"code":"visitPost","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" methods can be overridden."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Visitors that rewrite particular syntax nodes can be implemented as a subclass"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxRewriter","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":". Like a "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/SyntaxVisitor","type":"reference"},{"text":", a client needs to override","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the corresponding ","type":"text"},{"code":"visit","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" method accepting the syntax node of interest, and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"return a rewritten syntax node as a result.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Modifying the Syntax Tree","level":2,"anchor":"Modifying-the-Syntax-Tree"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The syntax trees provided by the SwiftSyntax library are immutable. All"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"modifications of the syntax tree are expressed as in-place updates to an","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"existing syntax tree, and return new syntax trees. SwiftSyntax provides a set","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"of high-level APIs for expressing these modifications. In general, data in"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"syntax nodes can be accessed via a getter and updated with a corresponding","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"with*"},{"text":" method. For example, the name of a class can be retrieved with the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ClassDeclSyntax\/identifier"},{"type":"text","text":" accessor, and replaced with the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ClassDeclSyntax\/with(_:_:)-3exln"},{"type":"text","text":" update function. This method returns"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"a new "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ClassDeclSyntax"},{"type":"text","text":" value."}]},{"text":"Building Syntax Trees","anchor":"Building-Syntax-Trees","level":2,"type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The swift-syntax package provides the ","type":"text"},{"code":"SwiftParser","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" module to parse arbitrary"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"source text into syntax trees. The Swift parser is appropriate for situations"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"where code is provided by a user, or cannot otherwise by predicted ahead of"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"time. However, there are often times when the structure of source code is known"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"at build time. For these cases, the SwiftSyntax library provides a method","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"for transparently interpreting string literals containing source code as syntax","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"trees when the "},{"code":"SwiftSyntaxBuilder","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" module is also imported:"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["import SwiftSyntax","import SwiftParser","import SwiftSyntaxBuilder","","\/\/ `file` is a source file syntax node containing the parsed value of the","\/\/ provided text.","let file: SourceFileSyntax =","  \"\"\"","  print(\"Hello, world!\")","  \"\"\""]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"String processing is not limited to string literals. Further interior string","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"interpolations can be used to parameterize the code in syntax generating"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"functions."}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["import SwiftSyntax","import SwiftParser","","func createClass(named name: String) -> ClassDeclSyntax {","  return \"\"\"","         class \\(raw: name) {}","         \"\"\"","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Using string literals and interpolation to build up syntax provides a fluid"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and natural API for building up complex syntax trees. This is generally"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"preferred to transforming syntax trees via a chain of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"with*"},{"text":" calls.","type":"text"}]}],"kind":"content"}],"references":{"doc://com.apple.swift-syntax/documentation/SwiftSyntax/RawSyntaxValidation":{"kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/RawSyntaxValidation","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A guide to using "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SWIFTSYNTAX_ENABLE_RAWSYNTAX_VALIDATION"},{"type":"text","text":" in third-party Swift macro packages."}],"role":"article","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/swiftsyntax\/rawsyntaxvalidation","title":"Raw Syntax Validation for Macro Testing"},"doc://com.apple.swift-syntax/documentation/SwiftSyntax/ClassDeclSyntax/identifier":{"title":"identifier","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.swift-syntax\/documentation\/SwiftSyntax\/ClassDeclSyntax\/identifier","fragments":[{"text":"var","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"identifier","kind":"identifier"},{"text":": ","kind":"text"},{"preciseIdentifier":"s:11SwiftSyntax05TokenB0V","text":"TokenSyntax","kind":"typeIdentifier"}],"deprecated":true,"kind":"symbol","role":"symbol","abstract":[],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftsyntax\/classdeclsyntax\/identifier","type":"topic"},"doc://com.apple.swift-syntax/documentation/SwiftSyntax/ClassDeclSyntax/with(_:_:)-3exln":{"abstract":[{"text":"Returns a new syntax node that has the child at ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"keyPath"},{"text":" replaced by","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"value"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"topic","title":"with(_:_:)","url":"\/documentation